args: In order to get back the stolen necklace, Malora\ninfiltrated the manor of a corrupt nobleman.\nHowever...
Now, then! You should be nice and frosty\nby now. ...Hm? Still conscious, are you?
*pant* *pant* Unfortunately for you,\nI am not so weak a woman.
Unyielding to the end, I see. How long will\nyou persist in this courageous facade, hm?
(This is bad. Despite my words, I'm nearly\nfrozen and losing consciousness.)
(I'm nearly at my limit. I can't believe I'm\ngoing to meet such a miserable end.\nAnd dressed like this, to boot.)
(Normally, this would be about when the\nHalidom gang would rush in and save me.\nNo such luck this time, though.)
(After all, I didn't tell any of them where\nI was going. This lone heroine gig's not\nall it's cracked up to be...)
(Farewell, {player_name}...\nI'm still happy I was able to spend time\nwith all of you at the Halidom...)
And now, let me see the expression of\nutmost despair frozen across your face\nas you breathe your last! Bwa ha ha!
What?! I was JUST getting to the good\npart!
So THIS is the Count's hidden workshop.
You seem to have toyed with more than\nyour fair share of lives. I cannot suffer a\nvillain like you to roam free.
Why are you here, General?\nBah, it doesn't matter! I need to—
I told you that I would find you, no matter\nwhere you were. The appointed time is\nlong past.
Ah, so you trailed me here...and ended up\nsaving me from that perverse man.\nWait, where is the Count?
Fled with his tail between his legs, has\nhe? Butler, where is the Count?
Guilt is written on his face, plain as day.\nAnd his gaze is fixed...here.
A hidden door. I see. He must have fled\nthrough here while you were assisting me.
The man is shrewd. He must be outside\nthe manor by now. I cannot believe I've\nallowed such a vile criminal to escape.
Why, there's no need to be so down.\nIt doesn't matter where he runs, after all.
I know well the minds of men.\nWill you trust me to track him?
I'll stay here outside town until the heat\ndies down, and then I'll—URAAAGH!
A trap?! Why is there a trap here?!\nDamn it all! I'm caught in this bloody net!
I knew you would escape through the\nwoods. It's almost embarrassingly cliché.
H-how dare you presume to understand\nmy intellect! Release me immediately!
That's a ＂No＂ with a capital N, I'm afraid.\nI'm handing you over to the general.\nBut first...
I need to give you my PERSONAL thanks\nfor the pleasure of our recent rendezvous.
Why, by that I mean... OHO HO HO HO HO!
S-stop! Don't come near me! No! NOOO!
Count Delchi has been incarcerated. He \nwas rather haggard when we found him.\nWhat did you do?
Oho ho. A lady never tells!
Now that I've finally gotten the necklace\nback, we'll all live happily ever after!
...Or maybe that's too optimistic. I failed to\nmeet the deadline we set together. Go on,\nValyx. Mete out my punishment.
Say, I know this is strange to say to an\nenemy, but I have one final request.
Will you return the necklace to its owner\nin my stead?
At the very least, I would like to finish\nmy work as Lady Starfall. So please...
Do not slough off your fool errand on me.\nReturn the necklace yourself.
I told you that if you could not resolve the\nsituation by sunset, I would deliver final\njudgment myself...to the Count.
It would hardly have been prudent of me to\nsit idly by and let you flounder indefinitely.
I know not the value of love. However,\nI cannot adjudicate she who would wager\nher life in the pursuit of justice.
If you do not believe my words, then think\nof it as amnesty granted in the spirit of\nDragonyule.
Valyx... Oho ho. So there's a charming\nman buried beneath that armor after all.
Hmph. This is a one-time display of mercy.\nKeep in mind that when we next meet,\nit shall be as enemies.
Oh, my. Perhaps we could even forego\nbeing enemies and simply meet as man\nand woman!

I'm starting to feel that even with your
brusque, disaffected, impenetrable
exterior, you may yet be within my
grasp, General. Oho ho.
And with that, my mission is complete.\nNevertheless...
Cooperating with an enemy general\ncertainly fits the criteria for a ＂Dragonyule\nmiracle,＂ if I do say so myself.
But perhaps ＂cooperation＂ is too strong a\nword. He and I simply kept to our\nprinciples.

Now, I'm off to deliver this necklace!
Though the loving sentiment it once bore
has perished, the light that remains is still
a thing of beauty!
